{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13959"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.15,0.07,0.6,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112101"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2341"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45878"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112101"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old man was brought into the Emergency Department after being found unconscious at the roadside. The duration of unresponsiveness is unknown. There is no available collateral history. He has no documented medical history and does not take any regular medications according to his electronic record.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate of 28/min, SpO2 of 98% on room air, and temperature of 37.2\u00b0C. He is obtunded but withdraws to pain. Pupils are equal and reactive. There are no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.31 (7.36\u20137.44)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 29 mmHg (35\u201345)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 80 mmHg (80\u2013100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 14 mmol/L (22\u201326)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135\u2013145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.8 mmol/L (3.5\u20135.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 100 mmol/L (98\u2013107)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate interpretation of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation","High anion gap metabolic acidosis without compensation","Mixed high anion gap metabolic and respiratory acidosis","High anion gap metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation","Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInterpreting acid\u2013base status requires systematic analysis of pH, primary disturbance, compensation, and anion gap. This patient has acidaemia (pH 7.31) with low bicarbonate (14 mmol/L) indicating metabolic acidosis. The PaCO2 is appropriately reduced (29 mmHg) indicating respiratory compensation. The anion gap can be calculated as: Na+ \u2212 (Cl\u2212 + HCO3\u2212) = 138 \u2212 (100 + 14) = 24 mmol/L (normal range 8\u201316 mmol/L), which is significantly elevated, suggesting accumulation of unmeasured anions such as ketones or lactate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh anion gap metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct interpretation. The low pH and bicarbonate indicate primary metabolic acidosis. Using Winter\u0027s formula for expected compensation: PaCO2 \u2248 (1.5 \u00d7 14) + 8 \u00b1 2 = 29 \u00b1 2 mmHg, which matches the measured PaCO2 of 29 mmHg, confirming appropriate respiratory compensation. The elevated anion gap points to conditions like diabetic ketoacidosis, alcoholic ketoacidosis, or lactic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal anion gap metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would show similar pH and bicarbonate values but with an anion gap within the normal range (8\u201316 mmol/L). This pattern is seen with gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss or renal tubular acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh anion gap metabolic acidosis without compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a low pH and bicarbonate but a PaCO2 that remains in the normal range (35\u201345 mmHg), indicating failure of respiratory compensation. This might occur in severe respiratory disease or central nervous system depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed high anion gap metabolic and respiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E would show low bicarbonate with an inappropriately high PaCO2 for the degree of metabolic acidosis. The PaCO2 would be higher than predicted by Winter\u0027s formula, indicating concurrent respiratory acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would present with an elevated pH (\u0026gt;7.44), low PaCO2 as the primary disturbance, and a compensatory decrease in bicarbonate. The acidaemic pH in this case excludes respiratory alkalosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation shows low pH, low bicarbonate, and a proportionately low PaCO2.","In metabolic acidosis, the anion gap helps differentiate between high anion gap causes (ketoacidosis, lactic acidosis) and normal anion gap causes.","The adequacy of respiratory compensation in metabolic acidosis can be estimated using Winter\u0027s formula: PaCO2 \u2248 (1.5 \u00d7 HCO3\u2212) + 8 \u00b1 2."],"references":["Verma AK, Roach P. The interpretation of arterial blood gases. Aust Prescr 2010;33:124-9. https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2010.059"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T20:18:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T20:19:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112101"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co